{{Infobox company | name = Banpu Public Company Limited | logo = BANPU logo.png | caption = | type = [[Public company|Public]] | traded_as = {{SET|BANPU}} | fate = | predecessor = | successor = | foundation = {{Start date|1983|05|16|df=y}}<ref name=SETCompanySummary>{{cite web|title=BANPU Company Summary|url=http://www.set.or.th/set/factsheet.do?symbol=BANPU|work=The Stock Exchange of Thailand|accessdate=9 November 2011}}</ref> | founder = | defunct = | location_city = [[Bangkok]] | location_country = [[Thailand]] | locations = | area_served = | key_people = Chanin Vongkusolkit (Chairman of the board)<ref name="Banpu-2017"/>{{RP|15}} | industry = Energy | products = [[Coal]], [[Electricity]] | services = | revenue = {{increase}} US$2,877 million {{small|(2017)}}<ref name="Banpu-2017">{{cite book|title=Greener and Smarter; Annual Report 2017|date=2018| publisher=Banpu|url=https://www.banpu.com/backoffice/upload/annual_report_46_98cc106dc9155a2d1df40c6fd4734467.pdf|accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref>{{RP|10}}<ref name=09SetFS>{{cite web|url=http://www.set.or.th/set/companyhighlight.do?symbol=BANPU&language=en&country=US|title=BANPU Public Company Limited|website=[[Stock Exchange of Thailand]]|accessdate=2011-02-12}}</ref> | operating_income = | net_income = {{increase}} US$234 million {{small|(2017)}}<ref name="Banpu-2017"/>{{RP|10}}<ref name=09SetFS /> | aum = | assets = {{increase}}US$8,223 million {{small|(2017)}}<ref name="Banpu-2017"/>{{RP|10}}<ref name=09SetFS /> | equity = {{increase}}US$3,211 million {{small|(2017)}}<ref name="Banpu-2017"/>{{RP|10}}<ref name=09SetFS /> | owner = | num_employees = | parent = | divisions = | subsid = Banpu Power | homepage = {{URL|www.banpu.com}} | footnotes = | intl = }}
'''Banpu Public Company Limited''' is a mining and power company in [[Thailand]]. It is the largest coal producer in Thailand<ref name=BP-20180818/> and also has [[coal mining]] operations in [[Indonesia]] and [[China]], and coal-fired [[Electricity generation|power generation]] operations in Thailand and China. Banpu plans also to invest in the Hong Sa [[lignite]] mine and power plant project in [[Laos]].<ref name=nation>{{cite web | work= The Nation | url= http://www.nationmultimedia.com/2007/03/31/business/business_30030721.php | title = Banpu Power seeks partner for Lao plant | date=2007-03-31 | accessdate=2008-03-09}}</ref>
Banpu's main coal resources are in Indonesia (26 million tonnes), Australia (14 million tonnes), and China (4.7 million tonnes). It expects its sales to rise to 45 million tonnes in 2018, up from 42 million tonnes in 2017.<ref name=BP-20180818>{{cite news |last1=Praiwan |first1=Yuthana |title=Banpu predicts strong coal price |url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/business/news/1523138/banpu-predicts-strong-coal-price |accessdate=19 August 2018 |work=Bangkok Post |date=18 August 2018}}</ref>
==Centennial Coal== In 2010 Banpu bought the Australian mining company [[Centennial Coal Company Ltd]] which operates [[Coal companies of Australia|five mines]] in [[New South Wales]] (NSW) supplying coal for export and approximately 40 percent of NSW's coal-fired electricity.<ref name=CCabout>{{cite web|title=About Us; Who we are|url=http://www.centennialcoal.com.au/About-Us/Who-We-Are.aspx|website=Centennial Coal|accessdate=18 September 2015}}</ref> The company sells approximately 40 percent of its coal to export markets, primarily for use in power stations and steel mills in Japan, Korea, Taiwan and Europe.<ref name=CCabout/>
Centennial Coal has been responsible for more than 900 pollution notices between 2000 and 2013 from the NSW [[Office of Environment and Heritage (New South Wales)|Environment Protection Authority]] (EPA). In 2015 it was responsible for a major release of coal fines into the [[Wollangambe River]] and World Heritage listed areas of the [[Blue Mountains National Park]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Clean up progressing for Wollangambe|url=http://www.epa.nsw.gov.au/epamedia/EPAMedia15073101.htm|website=NSW EPA|publisher=New South Wales Environment Protection Authority|accessdate=18 September 2015|date=2015-07-31}}</ref> Centennial Coal has been dumping mine effluent into the Wollangambe River for approximately 30 years, effectively killing large sections of it.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Belmer|first1=Nakia|last2=Tippler|first2=Carl|last3=Davies|first3=Peter J.|last4=Wright|first4=Ian A.|title=Impact of a coal mine waste discharge on water quality and aquatic ecosystems in the Blue Mountains World Heritage area|journal=Proceedings of the 7th Australian Stream Management Conference|url=http://www.bluemountains.org.au/documents/campaigns/wollangambe/7ASM-67%20Belmer%20et%20al%20%20Coal%20mine%20(Final%2025%20July%202014).pdf|accessdate=18 September 2015}}</ref> Between 2000-2015, Centennial's Clarence Colliery has been cited for more than 65 non-compliance breaches of its licence.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tan|first1=Monica|title=Coal miner's toxic wastes killing aquatic life in protected Blue Mountains river|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2015/jun/05/coal-miners-toxic-wastes-killing-aquatic-life-in-protected-blue-mountains-river|accessdate=4 January 2017|work=The Guardian|date=2015-06-05}}</ref> As of 2015, Centennial Coal has applied to extend the Springvale Mine, undermining swamps of "National Environmental Significance"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Muir|first1=Keith|title=The Perversion of National Heritage Protection Threatened heritage subversion—Centennial Coal's swamp scam|url=http://www.colongwilderness.org.au/news/2015/perversion-national-heritage-protection|website=The Colong Foundation for Wilderness Ltd|accessdate=18 September 2015}}</ref> and dumping up to 50 million litres a day of mine effluent into the [[Coxs River]] which also flows through the Blue Mountains World Heritage area and into [[Lake Burragorang|Sydney's drinking water catchments]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Court action to stop Springvale Mine polluting the Coxs River|url=https://www.colongwilderness.org.au/news/2016/court-action-stop-springvale-mine-polluting-coxs-river|website=The Colong Foundation for Wilderness Ltd|accessdate=4 January 2017}}</ref>
==Hong Sa Lignite== The Hong Sa Lignite project was founded by and belonged to Thai-Lao Lignite Co., Ltd. (TLL) and Hong Sa Lignite (Lao PDR) Co., Ltd. (HLL) pursuant to a concession from 1992-1994. In 2005, Banpu entered into a joint venture with TLL and HLL to develop the project, but this agreement was terminated in 2006. A [[United Nations Commission on International Trade Law|UNCITRAL]] arbitration found that the Lao government illegally terminated TLL's and HLL's concession (awarding it to Banpu) and ordered Laos to pay US$57 million in damages plus interest. Laos is refusing to pay the award despite its clear agreement with TLL and HLL, its government policy for international arbitration, and despite participating fully.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}
