[[File:Chicken_fat.jpg|thumb|right|Chicken fat]]
'''Chicken fat''' is [[fat]] obtained (usually as a [[by-product]]) from [[chicken]] [[Rendering (food processing)|rendering]] and [[Food processing|processing]]. Of the many [[Animal source foods|animal-sourced]] substances, chicken fat is noted for being high in [[linoleic acid]], an [[omega-6]] [[fatty acid]]. Linoleic acid levels are between 17.9% and 22.8%.<ref>[http://www.springerlink.com/content/0837289583682243/ The chemical composition of depot fats in chickens and turkeys]. M. K. Nutter, E. E. Lockhart and R. S. Harris. 1943. Journal of the American Oil Chemists' Society. 20:11, pp. 231-234.</ref> It is a common flavoring, additive or main component of [[chicken soup]]. It is often used in [[pet food]]s, and has been used in the production of [[biodiesel]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/christopherhelman/2012/02/17/making-cars-carnivores-tyson-venture-turns-animal-fat-into-diesel/ |title=Making Cars Carnivores: Tyson Venture Turns Animal Fat Into Diesel |date=February 17, 2012 |work=www.forbes.com |accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref> One method of converting chicken fat into biodiesel is through a process called supercritical methanol treatment.<ref>https://global.factiva.com/{{full citation needed|date=September 2018}}</ref>

