{{Distinguish|Environmental science}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}
{{Environment sidebar}}
'''Environmental studies''' is a multidisciplinary academic field which systematically studies [[human behavior|human interaction]] with the [[Natural environment|environment]] in the interests of solving complex problems. Environmental studies brings together the principles of the physical sciences, commerce/economics and social sciences so as to solve contemporary environmental problems. It is a broad field of study that includes the [[natural environment]], the [[built environment]], and the sets of relationships between them. The field encompasses study in basic principles of [[ecology]] and [[environmental science]], as well as associated subjects such as [[environmental ethics|ethics]], [[environmental geography|geography]], [[anthropology]], [[environmental policy|policy]], [[environmental politics|politics]], [[urban planning]], [[environmental law|law]], [[environmental economics|economics]], [[environmental philosophy|philosophy]], [[environmental sociology|sociology]] and [[environmental justice|social justice]], [[environmental planning|planning]], [[pollution control]] and [[natural resource management]].<ref>[[National Center for Education Statistics]]. [http://nces.ed.gov/pubs2002/cip2000/cip2000.asp?CIP2=03.0103 ''Classification of Instructional Programs (CIP 2000)- (03) NATURAL RESOURCES AND CONSERVATION''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090512100613/http://nces.ed.gov/pubs2002/cip2000/cip2000.asp?CIP2=03.0103 |date=12 May 2009 }}. Institute of Education Sciences, [[United States Department of Education]]. [Accessed 29 January 2010]</ref> There are also many degree programs in Environmental Studies including the [[Master's degree|Master of Environmental Studies]] and the [[Bachelor's degree|Bachelor of Environmental Studies]].

==History==
The [[State University of New York College of Environmental Science and Forestry|New York State College of Forestry at Syracuse University]] established a BS in environmental studies degree in the 1950s, awarding its first degree in 1956.<ref>[http://www.esf.edu/es/about.htm "About Environmental Studies at ESF,"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201031236/http://www.esf.edu/es/about.htm |date=1 December 2017 }} SUNY-ESF website. Accessed 28 November 2017.</ref> [[Middlebury College]] established the major there in 1965.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.middlebury.edu/academics/es|title=Environmental Studies - Middlebury|author=|date=|website=middlebury.edu|accessdate=29 April 2018|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171105051927/http://www.middlebury.edu/academics/es|archivedate=5 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

The [[Environmental Studies Association of Canada]] (ESAC) was established in 1993 "to further research and teaching activities in areas related to environmental studies in Canada".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.esac.ca/about/a-brief-history-of-esac/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-12 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120128074556/http://esac.ca/about/a-brief-history-of-esac/ |archivedate=28 January 2012 |df=dmy-all }} "A Brief History of ESAC". Accessed 12 March 2012.</ref> ESAC's magazine, ''[[A\J: Alternatives Journal]]'' was first published by [[Robert A. Paehlke]] on 4 July 1971.<ref>[http://www.alternativesjournal.ca/magazines/summer-1971-11 ''Alternatives''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106014646/http://www.alternativesjournal.ca/magazines/summer-1971-11 |date=6 January 2012 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.alternativesjournal.ca/the-alternatives-story "The Alternatives Story"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106020749/http://www.alternativesjournal.ca/the-alternatives-story |date=6 January 2012 }}</ref>

The [[Association for Environmental Studies and Sciences]] (AESS) was founded in 2008 as the first professional association in the interdisciplinary field of environmental studies in the United States. In 2010, the National Council for Science and the Environment (NCSE) agreed to advise and support the Association. The Association's scholarly journal, the ''Journal of Environmental Studies and Sciences'' (JESS), commenced publication in March 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aess.info|title=Association for Environmental Studies & Sciences AESSonline.org|author=|date=|website=AESSOnline.org|accessdate=29 April 2018|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310034932/http://aess.info/|archivedate=10 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The History and Development of AESS|url=https://aessonline.org/about-aess/history/|website=Association for Environmental Studies and Sciences|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161106060958/https://aessonline.org/about-aess/history/|archivedate=6 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

In the United States, many high school students are able to take environmental science as a college-level course.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apstudent.collegeboard.org/apcourse/ap-environmental-science|title=AP Environmental Science|publisher=''Collegeboard|accessdate=4 October 2018}}</ref> Over 500 colleges and universities in the United States offer environmental studies as a degree.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bigfuture.collegeboard.org/majors/natural-resources-conservation-environmental-studies|title=Major: Environmental Studies|publisher=''Collegeboard''|accessdate=4 October 2018}}</ref>

