'''Homonuclear molecules''', or '''homonuclear species''', are [[molecule]]s composed of only one type of [[Chemical element|element]]. Homonuclear molecules may consist of various numbers of [[atom]]s, depending on the element's properties. Some elements form molecules of more than one size. [[Noble gas]]es rarely form bonds, so they only have one atom. The most familiar homonuclear molecules are [[diatomic]], meaning they consist of two [[atom]]s, though not all diatomic molecules are homonuclear. Homonuclear diatomic molecules include [[hydrogen]] (H<sub>2</sub>), [[oxygen]] (O<sub>2</sub>), [[nitrogen]] (N<sub>2</sub>) and all of the [[halogen]]s. [[Ozone]] (O<sub>3</sub>) is a common triatomic homonuclear molecule. Homonuclear tetratomic molecules include [[arsenic]] (As<sub>4</sub>) and [[phosphorus]] (P<sub>4</sub>).

[[Allotrope]]s are different chemical forms of the same element (not containing any other element).  In that sense, allotropes are all homonuclear. Many elements have multiple allotropic forms. In addition to the most common form of gaseous oxygen, O<sub>2</sub>, and ozone, there are other [[allotropes of oxygen]]. [[Sulfur]] forms several [[allotropes of sulfur|allotropes]] containing different numbers of sulfur atoms, including [[diatomic element|diatomic]], triatomic, [[wikt:hexatomic|hexatomic]] and [[octatomic element|octatomic]] ([[disulfur|S<sub>2</sub>]], [[trisulfur|S<sub>3</sub>]], [[hexasulfur|S<sub>6</sub>]], [[octasulfur|S<sub>8</sub>]]) forms, though the first three are rare. The element [[carbon]] is known to have a number of homonuclear molecules, the best known being [[buckminsterfullerene]] or "buckyball".{{dubious|diamond, graphite, amorphous carbon, and possibly graphene might be better known than buckyballs|date=August 2018}}

