'''Pietra serena''' is a gray [[sandstone]] used extensively in [[Italian Renaissance|Renaissance]] [[Florence]] for architectural details.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |last1=Fratini |first1=F. |last2=Pecchioni |first2=E. |last3=Cantisani |first3=E. |last4=Rescic |first4=S. |last5=Vettori |first5=S. |title=Pietra Serena: the stone of the Renaissance |encyclopedia=Global Heritage Stone: Towards International Recognition of Building and Ornamental Stones |year=2015 |publisher=[[Geological Society of London]]|page=173|doi=10.1144/SP407.11 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IjyzCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA173}}</ref> It is also known as Macigno stone.<ref name=dictionary>{{cite encyclopedia |title=SIRENA STONE |encyclopedia=The Dictionary of Architecture |volume=7 |chapter=S |page=83 |year=1887 |publisher=Architectural Publication Society |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lJJZAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA1-PA83}}</ref> The material obtained at [[Fiesole]] is considered the best and it is also quarried at [[Arezzo]], [[Cortona]] and [[Volterra]].<ref name=dictionary /> Examples of its use in Florence include the interior [[pilaster]]s, [[entablature]]s, and other decorative elements of [[Brunelleschi]]'s [[Pazzi Chapel]] and [[Michelangelo]]'s [[Medici Chapel]].

